MITRE requires external support from the Contractor in conducting value stream improvement initiatives and rapid improvement events. The Contractor shall:
 
   Central Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 2 initiatives, each with up to 5 individual events
 o Resource should be located within 50 miles from Central Office location
 o Resource will support Central Office Value Stream Improvement (VSI) and Rapid Improvement Events (RI) Events
 
   Regional Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 1 initiative, with up to 5 individual events 
 o Resource(s) should be able to travel or located near Regional Office locations
 o Resource will support Regional Office VSI & RI Events
 
 Specific activities associated with these events include, but are not limited to:
 1. Confirming CISPS intake process is performed per standard work
 2. Consulting with and interviewing stakeholders to develop problem statement and business case. 
 3. Facilitating session to complete an event charter.
 4. Collecting and analyzing data including capturing data related to ROI. 
 5. Capturing mother and child value stream maps in electronic format, to include both current state and future state.  
 6. Developing action/implementation plans with timelines and milestones that correspond with the Improvement Approach phases and includes expected performance measures.  
 7. Creating a data collection/analysis plan for all measures that includes, but not limited to, data source/location, collection method, who will collect the data, and how the data will be represented (etc. pareto chart, histogram).
 8. Tracking and regularly reporting on progress towards achieving targets and closing performance gaps. 
 9. Coaching and mentoring CMS Lean Leads and CISPS who are facilitating VSIs in the VSI process using CMS developed methods/processes.
 10. Updating standard work documenting how to conduct events.
 11. Developing and implementing a plan to transition the VSI work to the appropriate party, as directed by CISPS. 
 
 CISPS, MITRE, and the Contractor shall establish methodologies for assessing potential improvement activities, including leveraging the CISPS intake process to prioritize events. Once a final decision is made by CISPS, the Contractor shall establish a charter that specifies the participants, problem statement, business case, scope, responsibilities, timeframe for completion of the activity(s), and any ongoing performance measures for measuring the success of the activity(s). Once the charter is approved by CISPS, the Contractor shall allocate resources to implement improvement activities that would meet the expectations and deliverables set forth in the charter. 
 
 All electronic correspondence with the customer in support of the above-mentioned activities shall include a designated MITRE resource. All improvement activities shall be tracked as part of the monthly Process Improvement Report (VSI Tracker) and shall inform other CMS administrative reports, including the MITRE Monthly Progress Report. The Contractor is responsible for tracking the logistics, planning, level of effort, and costs for each Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event.
 
 Task 3: Lean Development Support
 MITRE requires external support from the Contractor in providing lean development support. The Contractor shall:
 
   Provide up to 2 months of Lean Development Support (0.5 to 1.0 resource), working in combination with an assigned MITRE lean support resource. 
   Specific activities associated with this support include, but are not limited to:
 1. Continued development of an internal capacity for facilitating and coaching Lean methodologies (e.g., Lean Ambassador, Lean Leads and Managers as Coaches) in order to position CMS to achieve efficiencies, reduce variation across components, and apply standard work as fundamental to process improvements.
 2. Providing governance support to guide and monitor CMS continu

column77:
Media Campaign/Visual Design Support 
 The Contractor shall provide graphics design development support for the CMS Interoperability Initiative and the associated media campaign. In addition to development activities, the Contractor shall participate in planned working sessions with CMS personnel and other members of the MITRE delivery team to assist in creating impactful and accurate materials to communicate strategy and methodology, and to create templates which may be used by the team for ongoing activities and communications.
 
 Working sessions may be by phone or in person as needed. 
 
 The Contractor shall support ongoing and iterative creation of designs that, at a high level, articulate the recommended design patterns to best represent the Interoperability Initiative strategy and methodology. These concept designs shall be developed at the direction of the MITRE Project Leader  or Designee.
 
 After MITRE has reviewed the concept designs, the Contractor shall generate mockups/drafts, delivered in the format defined by the MITRE, via email to the MITRE Project Leader or Designee.
 
 The Contractor shall:
 1) Work as an integrated team with MITRE, Alliance Partners, and Subcontractors.
 2) Participate in work sessions and other meetings to review recommendations and develop presentation materials, including updates to the CMS Interoperability Road Map.
 3) Design a communications and branding strategy related to the MyHealthEData initiative and the interoperability proposed rule.
 4) At the discretion of the Project Leader, assist in development of communications materials, graphics designs, branding, and coordinating with CMS on ad hoc basis.
 5) Ensure all materials delivered under contract meet Federal Government 508 Compliance standards, consistent with CMS style guides.
 6) Ensure all materials and methods used are free from licensing/fee payments, copyrights, and trademarks.

PERIOD OF PERFORMANCE:  BASE YEAR:  09/20/2017 THROUGH 09/19/2018;                     OPTION YEAR 1:  09/20/2018 THROUGH 09/19/2019;                   OPTION PERIOD 2:  09/20/2019 THROUGH 09/30/2019  ALL TERMS AND CONDITIONS TO THE FFRDC AWARD ARE APPLICABLE TO THIS AWARD.
column46: ALL OTHER PROFESSIONAL, SCIENTIFIC, AND TECHNICAL SERVICES
column77:
Program Management Support
 The Contractor shall provide support to best enable NIH oversight of the data Commons Consortium membership as they perform their responsibilities as defined through the Other Transactional Authority (OTA) negotiation process.  This includes the following activities:
 
 1. Within 15 business days of execution, the Contractor shall provide a strategy for establishing program management controls for the Data Commons, and the ongoing efforts consortium that underlies is. This will be vetted with key NIH stakeholders, modified as needed, and then finalized.  Key attributes of the strategy will include some or all of the following (to include mechanisms of achieving these goals):
 a. Risk enumeration
 b. Mitigation enumeration (based on a.)
 c. Integration of consortium activities
 d. Cross-team coordination 
 e. Dependency enumeration 
 f. Program governance 
 g. Data governance
 h. Standards assurance  
 i. Accountability management
 j. Financial tracking (cost, value)
 k. Infrastructure planning
 l. Enumeration of continuous improvement opportunities
 
 The required contents of the strategy document will be enumerated by MITRE within the first 5 business days of this contract, except by mutual agreement of MITRE, NIH, and Contractor.  It is expected that a 1-page document will suffice for these purposes.  
 
 2. Through this effort, including during finalization of the strategy for program management controls, the Contractor shall begin execution of portions that have been mutually agreed.  This means that supporting the overall management of this effort by ensuring the timely completion and coordination of objectives, refining NIH-derived metrics of success, and enhancing overall reporting and communication on the program can begin immediately.  Specific activities to be undertaken immediately include the following:
 a. Coordinate with Consortium project management personnel
 b. Monitor general project health
 c. Maintain master schedule of milestones and dependencies for all Data Commons activities based on the schedule provided initially by NIH
 d. Facilitate interdependent issues and risks mitigation
 e. Facilitate critical program meetings (no more than 12)
 f. Create executive-level presentations (no more than 6)
 g. Support and enforce adherence to project communications plan (mechanism TBD)
 h. Manage stakeholder engagement metrics (no more than monthly)
 i. Provide other support to Program Lead, as required and as appropriate for the position
 
 Contractor will provide reports on the activities undertaken and outcomes every 20 business days, in a format mutually agreeable to Contractor, NIH, and MITRE.  It is expected that a 1-3-page document will suffice for these purposes. 
 
 Task 3: Data Management Support
 The Contractor shall provide support to best enable NIH Data Management for the Data Commons Consortium membership as they perform their responsibilities as defined through the Other Transactional Authority (OTA) negotiation process. This includes the following activities:
 1. Within 15 business days of execution, the Contractor shall provide a strategy for establishing data management controls for the Data Commons, including (but not exclusive to) TOPMed and GTEx data and metadata, and the ongoing consortium efforts that underlies this. This will be vetted with key NIH stakeholders, modified as needed, and then finalized. Key attributes of the strategy will include some or all of the following (to include mechanisms of achieving these goals):
 a. Data migration (to cloud, inter-cloud, download from cloud)
 b. Data currency maintenance
 c. Metadata management
 d. Metadata configuration and management in SRA/SDDP/fusera or other NIH-prescribed access control mechanisms
 e. Data access control and user authentication
 f. Cloud data storage configuration and administration
 g. Data use measurement
 h. Data storage cost forecasts
 i. Data storage use forecasts
 j. Data governance
 k. Data availability communications

column77:
Dr. Spite will provide liquid-chromatagraphy/tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS) services as a 
 subcontractor in support of Stage B VITA, entitled  Prevention of anastomotic intimal hyperplasia 
 by a resolvin-eluting perivascular device . Collaboration on this project is completely feasible 
 given preliminary data and state-of-the-art lipidomics platform. As you know from our extensive 
 ongoing collaborations, we have expertise with LC-MS/MS analysis of lipid mediators and have 
 instrumentation (AB Sciex Qtrap 5500) that enables the identification and sensitive quantification 
 of lipid mediators in biological matrices.
 
 In line with stipulated Milestones, we will perform analysis to validate the structural integrity 
 and concentration of the resolvin D1 (RvD1) analog, benzo-diacetylenic-17R-RvD1 methyl ester 
 (BDA-RvD1) in samples. I will also provide scientific consultation on an ad hoc basis as part of 
 this program.
 Milestone 1: Device optimization-testing for active compound stability
 Milestone 2:  Non-GLP efficacy study, ovine model
 Milestone 3: GLP efficacy study, ovine model

column77:
State Waivers under Section 1332
 The Contractor shall:
 
   Provide Subject Matter Expertise (SME) and develop template applications, waivers, and instructions for states and insurance oversight agencies to apply for state innovation waivers authorized under section 1332 of the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act. The Contractor shall partner with MITRE to provide support to CMS staff during state engagements, including, but not limited to phone calls, in-person meetings, virtual meetings and webinars.
   The Contractor SMEs are required to format and develop: 
 o Guidance/Waiver Models/White papers for consumption by State Legislatures / State Department of Insurance (DOI);
 o Laying out multiple templates of possible 1332 waivers; and  
 o Engagement/Approach strategies for up to 6 States.
   The SMEs provided by the Contractor are expected to include, but not limited to senior level experts with several years of experience and extensive hands-on knowledge on 1332 waivers to produce fast turnaround templates, instructions, and engagements with states.

column46: ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTING SERVICES
column77:
1. AVERT tool and user manual updates and maintenance. The subcontractor will improve AVERT as new information becomes available. Upon technical direction, the Subcontractor shall make changes to the functionality, charts, graphs, outputs, and inter-workings of AVERT or add-on modules that enhance AVERT s capabilities. The Subcontractor shall continue to support AVERT upgrades, update regional datasets, user manual edits, fixes, and maintenance based on needs specified by EPA and ERG. 
 2. AVERT and related training and outreach. The subcontractors will assist with expand training materials and necessary outreach for AVERT and related EE/RE programs and emissions methods. This support may include online training content, live presentations, and phone and webinar outreach.
 3. Clean energy and climate analysis support. The Subcontractor shall support EPA in its efforts to help state and local governments further climate and energy policy goals. The Subcontractor shall perform analysis; review documentation, tools, or models; develop materials; and make recommendations to inform EPA via memos, graphics, charts, graphs, or any other medium as directed.
 4. Technical assistance. The Subcontractor shall provide overall technical assistance to help EPA and targeted stakeholders to properly use AVERT. Technical assistance could also involve addressing clean energy (EE/RE)-related questions posed by EPA, states, or localities.
 5. Energy efficiency tool. The subcontractor will update and enhance the Energy Efficiency Savings Tool, an Excel-based spreadsheet that analyzes energy efficiency within the context of power sector policies and planning. Updates may include adding modules within the tool. Enhancements may include updated data inputs, enhanced functionality, and transition from Excel to a web-based platform.

column77:
EPA will provide technical assistance on clean energy to state utility economic and air regulators, state clean energy policy makers, utilities, and other stakeholders on policy, rate and/or program options that help remove barriers to clean energy. Upon technical direction from EPA and ERG, the subcontractor shall develop supporting materials. The subcontractor shall be involved in this assistance and may be
 involved in discussions with states, utilities and stakeholder groups.
 The subcontractor will also conduct research and analysis on a quick-turnaround and longer-lead basis.
 The product of these requests will be used to support policies that remove barriers to clean energy, recognize the effect on emissions from utilizing clean energy resources, and help create a business case for increased clean energy investment. Products may include technical tools and supporting documentation and materials for use internal or external to EPA.

Subcontractor activities are described in this Statement of Work and shall include provision of laboratory services including:
 
   Sample receipt and storage. 
   Supplies. Other than shipping costs and the items listed above, the subcontractor will provide all equipment, supplies, materials, and test kits needed to complete the assays.
   Sample Handling. Adherence to best practices that follow NIH guidelines for human biospecimen handling, storage, shipping and tracking within the NIH Intramural Research Program is required. assays will be run in batches of 50), re-freeze remaining plasma sample to transfer to Broad Institute, and re-freeze remaining whole blood sample to transfer to SSS.
   Sample Testing. The subcontractor will perform assays according to the test SOPs, procedures, and vendor product inserts provided for each test. 
   Quality Control. Quality control activities will be conducted to identify any batch effect caused by equipment, reagents, or processing procedures. When an analyte control is available, it will be run in all batches to determine inter-batch variation

Attachment A
 Scope of Work for Cohort 4 
 
 Background: Healthcare-associated infections, or HAIs, are a highly significant cause of illness and death for patients in the U.S. health care system. At any given time, HAIs affect one out of every 25 hospital inpatients. More than a million of these infections occur across our health care system every year, leading to significant patient harm and the annual loss of tens of thousands of lives, and costing billions of dollars each year. Some of the most prevalent HAIs include: surgical site infections (SSIs), Catheter-Associated Urinary Tract Infections (CAUTI), Central-Line Associated Blood Stream Infections (CLABSI), and ventilator-associated pneumonia (VAP). It is estimated that CAUTIs affect approximately 250,000 hospital patients per year, and approximately 40,000 CLABSI cases occur annually with a mortality rate from 12 to 25 percent.
 
 Key Personnel:  The following individual/positions are designated as key personnel under this Agreement:
 [____] 
 
 Pre-existing Subcontractor Intellectual Property:  The Parties acknowledge that Subcontractor plans to use and/or deliver the following pre-existing Intellectual Property Rights in its performance of this Agreement:
 
 Each participating State Lead (SL) will work to coordinate the program in their state, understand program onboarding and educational materials in order to coach units appropriately, and is responsible for performing the following tasks. 
 
 Tasks:
 1. Attend in-person kick-off meeting in Chicago on June 7, 2018 (travel for up to two (2) individuals to be covered by HRET) prior to the start of the project 
 a. If unable to attend in-person kick-off meeting, SL must watch all onboarding webinars and provide documentation of viewership
 b. Recommend identifying and recruiting at least one state-level clinical mentor to provide clinical support for units throughout the program. If clinical mentor is identified, (s)he must watch all onboarding webinars and provide documentation of viewership
 2. Develop and submit State Implementation Plan (template to be provided by HRET) after the kick-off meeting to their HRET Quality Improvement Coach. The plan should evaluate the current CLABSI and CAUTI prevention strategies and how the SL and clinical mentor can complement existing strategies and address gaps that may exist, as well as plans for sustaining improvement. HRET will provide a template for SLs to use and due date at the Kick-off.
 3. Recruit and register eligible units to participate in Cohort 4 by July 15, 2018. 
 a. Eligible units are those that meet the established criteria for persistently elevated infection rates (PEIR) as confirmed by NHSN TAP reports
 4. 90% of eligible participating units must submit ICU Assessment (template to be provided by HRET) into CDS within the submission timeframe 
 5. 90% of eligible participating units must submit ICU Action Plan (template to be provided by HRET) into CDS within four (4) weeks after receiving ICU Assessment results 
 6. SL and clinical mentor to review and become familiar with programmatic and educational materials prior to unit participation in project to support their coaching efforts
 7. Ensure units meet program education and data requirements and intervene as soon as challenges become apparent (within 30 days). These requirements include:
 a. Education requirements:
 i. participation in all onboarding webinars hosted by HRET
 ii. accessing HRET e-learning modules and other project toolkit materials based on needs identified in action plan
 iii. attending monthly virtual learning group (VLG) webinars hosted by HRET 
 b. Data requirements: 
 i. conferring rights to HRET s NHSN group (instructions for conferring rights will be provided at the kick-off meeting)
 ii. If NHSN rights are not conferred to HRET for data submission, SL must submit all required data on a monthly basis to HRET (details for data metrics will be provide at kick-off meeting)
 8. Have, at a minimum, monthly check-ins with all PEIR units, including those making good progress. Monthly check-ins should include a review of the unit s:
 a. Successes and challenges
 b. Rates and trends of CLABSI and/or CAUTI rates and device utilization
 c. Progress in unit s action plan 
 9. Have monthly check-ins with HRET Quality Improvement Coach
 10. Attend monthly coaching calls and Virtual Learning group (VLG) webinars hosted by HRET
 a. Identify unit presenters as needed for VLGs
 11. Submit quarterly progress reports (template to be provided by HRET), which will include tracking progress to the ICUs  action plans, through platform provided by HRET 
 12. Submit at least one case study (template to be provided by HRET) on implementation successes and/or challenges from participating units
 13. Coordinate and attend unit site visits (all costs to be covered by SL) to 30% of eligible participating units (site visits may be shared between SL and clinical mentor).
 a. At least one site visit to include National Project Team (NPT) subject matter experts (SME) (travel expenses for NPT SMEs to be covered by HRET)
 b. Submit site visit report for each site visit into CDS (template to be provided by HRET)
 i. Site visit report to be submitted within 30 days of site visit
 14. OPTIONAL: Hold at least one (1) in-person state-level meeting (all costs to be covered by SL)
 15. OPTIONAL: Attend cohort close-out meeting if scheduled by HRET (travel for up to two (2) individuals to be covered by HRET)
  
 ATTACHMENT B

Media Campaign/Visual Design Support 
 The Contractor shall provide graphics design development support for the CMS Interoperability Initiative and the associated media campaign. In addition to development activities, the Contractor shall participate in planned working sessions with CMS personnel and other members of the MITRE delivery team to assist in creating impactful and accurate materials to communicate strategy and methodology, and to create templates which may be used by the team for ongoing activities and communications.
 
 Working sessions may be by phone or in person as needed. 
 
 The Contractor shall support ongoing and iterative creation of designs that, at a high level, articulate the recommended design patterns to best represent the Interoperability Initiative strategy and methodology. These concept designs shall be developed at the direction of the MITRE Project Leader  or Designee.
 
 After MITRE has reviewed the concept designs, the Contractor shall generate mockups/drafts, delivered in the format defined by the MITRE, via email to the MITRE Project Leader or Designee.
 
 The Contractor shall:
 1) Work as an integrated team with MITRE, Alliance Partners, and Subcontractors.
 2) Participate in work sessions and other meetings to review recommendations and develop presentation materials, including updates to the CMS Interoperability Road Map.
 3) Design a communications and branding strategy related to the MyHealthEData initiative and the interoperability proposed rule.
 4) At the discretion of the Project Leader, assist in development of communications materials, graphics designs, branding, and coordinating with CMS on ad hoc basis.
 5) Ensure all materials delivered under contract meet Federal Government 508 Compliance standards, consistent with CMS style guides.
 6) Ensure all materials and methods used are free from licensing/fee payments, copyrights, and trademarks.

MITRE requires external support from the Contractor in conducting value stream improvement initiatives and rapid improvement events. The Contractor shall:
 
   Central Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 2 initiatives, each with up to 5 individual events
 o Resource should be located within 50 miles from Central Office location
 o Resource will support Central Office Value Stream Improvement (VSI) and Rapid Improvement Events (RI) Events
 
   Regional Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 1 initiative, with up to 5 individual events 
 o Resource(s) should be able to travel or located near Regional Office locations

 Specific activities associated with these events include, but are not limited to:
 1. Confirming CISPS intake process is performed per standard work
 2. Consulting with and interviewing stakeholders to develop problem statement and business case. 
 3. Facilitating session to complete an event charter.
 4. Collecting and analyzing data including capturing data related to ROI. 
 5. Capturing mother and child value stream maps in electronic format, to include both current state and future state.  
 6. Developing action/implementation plans with timelines and milestones that correspond with the Improvement Approach phases and includes expected performance measures.  
 7. Creating a data collection/analysis plan for all measures that includes, but not limited to, data source/location, collection method, who will collect the data, and how the data will be represented (etc. pareto chart, histogram).
 8. Tracking and regularly reporting on progress towards achieving targets and closing performance gaps. 
 9. Coaching and mentoring CMS Lean Leads and CISPS who are facilitating VSIs in the VSI process using CMS developed methods/processes.
 10. Updating standard work documenting how to conduct events.
 11. Developing and implementing a plan to transition the VSI work to the appropriate party, as directed by CISPS. 
 
 CISPS, MITRE, and the Contractor shall establish methodologies for assessing potential improvement activities, including leveraging the CISPS intake process to prioritize events. Once a final decision is made by CISPS, the Contractor shall establish a charter that specifies the participants, problem statement, business case, scope, responsibilities, timeframe for completion of the activity(s), and any ongoing performance measures for measuring the success of the activity(s). Once the charter is approved by CISPS, the Contractor shall allocate resources to implement improvement activities that would meet the expectations and deliverables set forth in the charter. 
 
 All electronic correspondence with the customer in support of the above-mentioned activities shall include a designated MITRE resource. All improvement activities shall be tracked as part of the monthly Process Improvement Report (VSI Tracker) and shall inform other CMS administrative reports, including the MITRE Monthly Progress Report. The Contractor is responsible for tracking the logistics, planning, level of effort, and costs for each Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event.

Continued development of an internal capacity for facilitating and coaching Lean methodologies (e.g., Lean Ambassador, Lean Leads and Managers as Coaches) in order to position CMS to achieve efficiencies, reduce variation across components, and apply standard work as fundamental to process improvements.

Dr. Hernandez-Diaz will bring to the project her expertise in studying the safety and
 effectiveness of pharmacotherapy during pregnancy using a variety of study designs and
 data sources, her expertise in epidemiologic methods especially as they relate to
 pregnancy research, and her clinical background. She will be closely involved in the study
 design and protocol development, as well as the study conduct and analyses for each
 aim. Dr. Hernandez-Diaz will contribute her experience in pregnancy research using large
 administrative databases by working closely with Dr. Huybrechts on the creation of the
 analytic datasets for each aim, which will be housed at Brigham and Women's Hospital,
 including any changes to be made to the existing linked mothers/infants dataset. She will
 provide input to the development of the study protocols anddata abstraction forms to be
 used for the medical record review as part of the validation studies; and will critically
 review the final protocol versions and analyses findings. Throughout the project, Dr.
 Hernandez-Diaz will participate in weekly meetings with Dr. Huybrechts and other team members to review the research progress. She will participate in drafting written summaries for inclusion in progress reports to the sponsor, and will help prepare conference presentations and publishable manuscripts.

column77:
Illumina is currently working with a video animation subcontractor to produce a short, narrated animated video that depicts how naloxone works to prevent an opioid overdose. The video will be used in a CAPT course on overdose prevention.
 
 For this project, the video animation subcontractor will set up a recording session and re-record the animation script with the narrator, Lili Wexu. The subcontractor will edit the new recording into the existing animation and subsequently revise the animation to ensure congruence.
 
 This additional recording was necessitated by a post-production review of the rough cut of the animation, which revealed areas of the film that needed to be clarified with additional narration.
 
 EDC/CAPT will work with Illumina and the subcontractor via virtual meeting to complete the recording, and via email and conference call to review the edits. EDC/CAPT will work directly with Illumina s subcontractor personnel.
